@startuml world_layer

package "World Layer" {

    ' ==========================================
    ' ENUMS & DATA STRUCTURES
    ' ==========================================
    enum TileType {
        AIR
        SOLID
        BRICK
        QUESTION
        EMPTY_BLOCK
        PIPE_TOP
        PIPE_BODY
        CLOUD
        WATER_TOP
        WATER
        LAVA
        DEATH_ZONE
        FLAG_POLE
        CASTLE
    }

    class Tile {
        + type : TileType
        + rect : Rect
        + position : Vector2D
        + hasItem : bool
        + itemType : std::string
        + active : bool
        + isUsed : bool
    }

    ' ==========================================
    ' CORE WORLD CLASSES
    ' ==========================================
    class TileMap {
        - tiles : std::vector<std::vector<Tile>>
        + pixelWidth : int
        + pixelHeight : int
        + TileMap()
        + render(renderer: Renderer&, camera: Camera&): void
        + getTileAt(x: float, y: float): Tile&
        + getTilesInRect(rect: Rect): std::vector<Tile*>
        + clear(): void
    }

    class Camera {
        + x : float
        + y : float
        + x_min : float
        + target : Vector2D
        + viewport : Rect
        + Camera(viewportW: int, viewportH: int)
        + update(mapWidth: int): void
    }

    ' ==========================================
    ' FACTORIES & LOADERS
    ' ==========================================
    class LevelLoader {
        + static loadLevel(path: std::string, outMap: TileMap&, outEntities: std::vector<Entity*>&): bool
        - static parseTiles(data: json, outMap: TileMap&): void
        - static parseEntities(data: json, outEntities: std::vector<Entity*>&): void
        - static loadDefaultLevel(outMap: TileMap&): bool
    }

    class EntityFactory {
        + static createEntity(type: std::string, pos: Vector2D, config: json): Entity*
    }

    ' ==========================================
    ' RELATIONSHIPS & DEPENDENCIES
    ' ==========================================
    TileMap *-- "many" Tile : contains >
    Tile o-- TileType : uses >
    
    LevelLoader ..> TileMap : populates >
    LevelLoader ..> EntityFactory : uses >
    
    TileMap ..> Camera : culls off-screen tiles using >
}

package "Domain Layer (Entities)" {
    abstract class Entity
}

' External dependencies
EntityFactory ..> Entity : instantiates >

note right of LevelLoader
  Reads assets/maps/world_X_Y.json
  Fills the TileMap and uses EntityFactory 
  to populate the initial spawn list.
end note

note right of Camera
  Clamps to map boundary.
  Never scrolls backward 
  (x = max(x, x_min)).
end note

@enduml

Key Components Explained
TileType & Tile: Represents the static grid of the game world. 
Each Tile holds spatial data (Rect, position) and logic flags (e.g., hasItem, isUsed)
to handle interactions like Mario hitting a QUESTION block or breaking a BRICK block.

TileMap: Manages the 2D array of tiles. Its render() method is 
highly optimized—it takes the Camera as an argument to perform 
frustum culling, ensuring it only draws tiles currently visible 
on the screen, rather than iterating over thousands of off-screen tiles.

Camera: Follows Mario's position (target) but strictly 
enforces map boundaries. As specified in your edge cases, 
it implements the x = max(x, x_min) logic to prevent 
the player from scrolling the screen backward.

LevelLoader: The bridge between your raw JSON files and the engine. 
It parses world_X_Y.json, constructs the static TileMap, 
and reads the entity spawn definitions. 
It includes fallback logic (loadDefaultLevel) 
to prevent hard crashes if a JSON file is missing or corrupted.

EntityFactory: A strict Factory Method implementation. 
When the LevelLoader or a game event (like hitting a block) 
requests a "Goomba" or a "Mushroom", this factory interprets 
the request and allocates the correct concrete Entity subclass.